to pursue a very different goal: a neighborhood with national retailers and increasingly affluent residents. The Roots of Urban Renaissance demonstrates that gentrification was not imposed on an unwitting community by unscrupulous developers or opportunistic outsiders. Rather, it grew from the neighborhood’s grassroots, producing a legacy that benefited some longtime residents and threatened others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh  aArchitects' Renewal Committee in Harlem.  aHarlem Commonwealth Council.  aHarlem Urban Development.  aJ. Max Bond.  aMorningside Heights.  aPreservation of the East Harlem Triangle.  abrownstones.  acommercial development.  agentrification.  ahousing abandonment.  alow-income housing.  amodel cities.  anew york state affordable housing.  aurban homesteading.  aurban renewal.1 aSugrue, Thomas J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Architecture and Design 2023z9783111318097oZDB-23-DAD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2023 Englishz978311131903208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074973140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691243474?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691243474423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691243474/original  a978-3-11-074973-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-131903-2  EBOOK PA